"1409","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":46,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":119,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Wetewode was born about 1336, in Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England, his father, Thomas of Bradford Wetewode, was 21 and his mother, Abigail Horsley, was 21. He married Agnes de Bradford about 1355, in Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1336–":"umbes 1336–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1338–1442":"1338–1442","1356–1447":"1356–1447","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1316–1409":"1316–1409","1382":"1382","1316":"1316","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1447":"1447","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","Abt 1355":"umbes 1355","1356":"1356","1334":"1334","1455":"1455","about 1336":"umbes 1336","1453":"1453","1442":"1442","1409":"1409","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"about 1336–":"noin 1336–Kuollut","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1338–1442":"1338–1442","1356–1447":"1356–1447","1316–Male":"1316–Kuollut","1316–1409":"1316–1409","1382":"1382","1316":"1316","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1447":"1447","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","Abt 1355":"noin 1355","1356":"1356","1334":"1334","1455":"1455","about 1336":"noin 1336","1453":"1453","1442":"1442","1409":"1409","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northum